  "question": "Muon drops AdamW's second moment state, so why did the native expert-Muon run consume more memory and run slower?",
  "answer": "Native PyTorch Muon halves persistent expert optimizer state, but it replaces fused AdamW with expensive Newton-Schulz matrix orthogonalization and uses large transient update/Gram workspaces. The native wrapper also split DSv4 rank-3 expert banks into 1152 rank-2 Parameter views per rank, adding optimizer overhead. A batched expert-bank Muon implementation fixes the wrapper/temporary memory problem, but Newton-Schulz remains too slow to promote.",
  "code_changes": {
    "optimizer": "sources/wip/torchtitan/torchtitan/components/optimizer.py",
    "new_optimizer_impl": "BatchedMuonExpertParams",
    "selector": "TORCHTITAN_OPTIMIZER_MUON_IMPL=batched or CANARY_OPTIMIZER_MUON_IMPL=batched",
    "default_chunk_matrices": 32,
    "tested_chunk_matrices": 4,
    "memory_fix": "The final implementation applies Muon chunk by chunk and no longer materializes a full per-parameter update tensor plus full output tensor.",
    "numerics_fix": "Newton-Schulz normalization computes the Frobenius norm in FP32 before casting back to the selected compute dtype, avoiding the native ROCm BF16 norm FPE seen in stock torch.optim.Muon."
  },
